 235	## Middleware
 236	
 237	Middleware provides a way to execute code before handlers are invoked, enabling cross-cutting concerns like authentication, logging, validation, and request preprocessing.
 238	
 239	### Defining Middleware
 240	
 241	Create a middleware class that implements the `RestateMiddleware` interface:
 242	
 243	```ts
 244	import { RestateMiddleware, RestateBaseContext } from 'deepkit-restate';
 245	
 246	class AuthenticationMiddleware implements RestateMiddleware {
 247	 async execute(ctx: RestateBaseContext): Promise<void> {
 248	 // Access context properties like headers, request data, etc.
 249	 const headers = ctx.request?.headers;
 250	
 251	 // Perform authentication logic
 252	 if (!headers?.authorization) {
 253	 throw new Error('Authentication required');
 254	 }
 255	
 256	 // Middleware can modify context or perform side effects
 257	 console.log('Request authenticated');
 258	 }
 259	}
 260	```
 261	
 262	### Applying Middleware
 263	
 264	#### Service-Level Middleware
 265	
 266	Apply middleware to all handlers in a service:
 267	
 268	```ts
 269	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>().middleware(AuthenticationMiddleware)
 270	class UserService implements UserServiceHandlers {
 271	 @restate.handler()
 272	 async create(username: string): Promise<User> {
 273	 // AuthenticationMiddleware runs before this handler
 274	 return new User(username);
 275	 }
 276	}
 277	```
 278	
 279	#### Handler-Level Middleware
 280	
 281	Apply middleware to specific handlers:
 282	
 283	```ts
 284	@restate.service<UserServiceApi>()
 285	class UserService implements UserServiceHandlers {
 286	 @restate.handler().middleware(ValidationMiddleware)
 287	 async create(username: string): Promise<User> {
 288	 // ValidationMiddleware runs before this handler
 289	 return new User(username);
 290	 }
